\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 Haploinsufficiency 
\f1\b0 occurs when one copy of the gene is 
\f2\i lost 
\f1\i0 or 
\f2\i nonfunctional 
\f1\i0 and the remaining copy is 
\f0\b not sufficient 
\f1\b0 for a normal phenotype. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Haplosufficiency 
\f1\b0 describes when the remaining copy of the gene is 
\f0\b sufficient 
\f1\b0 for a normal phenotype. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Proto-oncogenes 
\f1\b0 are genes that can become 
\f0\b oncogenes 
\f1\b0 (cancer-causing genes) due to 
\f0\b gain-of-function 
\f1\b0 mutations. Gain-of-function mutations cause 
\f0\b too much 
\f1\b0 protein to be made or production of an 
\f0\b over-active 
\f1\b0 protein. Cancerous growth occurs as a result because proto-oncogenes are normally involved in 
\f2\i cell cycle control
\f1\i0 . \cb1 \

\f2\i \cb3 Proto-oncogenes 
\f1\i0 follow the 
\f0\b one hit hypothesis
\f1\b0 , which states that a gain-of-function mutation in 
\f2\i one 
\f1\i0 copy of the gene turns it into a 
\f2\i oncogene
\f1\i0 . \cb1 \
\cb3 \

\f0\b Tumor-suppressor genes 
\f1\b0 are genes that become cancerous as a result of 
\f0\b loss-of-function 
\f1\b0 mutations because they are normally needed to 
\f2\i suppress 
\f1\i0 cancerous growth. \cb1 \

\f2\i \cb3 Tumor-suppressor genes 
\f1\i0 follow the 
\f0\b two hit hypothesis
\f1\b0 , which states that a loss-of-function mutation in 
\f2\i both 
\f1\i0 copies of the gene are needed to make it cancer-causing. Thus, tumor-suppressor genes are 
\f0\b haplosufficient
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Null alleles 
\f1\b0 come from mutations that cause the alleles to lack normal function. Tumor-suppressor genes have 
\f2\i null alleles 
\f1\i0 when they become cancer-causing. \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \uc0\u9679  
\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 p53 
\f1\b0 is an important tumor-suppressor gene that is known as the 
\f0\b guardian of the cell
\f1\b0 . It is 
\f0\b upregulated 
\f1\b0 to prevent cells from becoming cancerous. \cb1 \

\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \uc0\u9679  
\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 p21 
\f1\b0 is another tumor-suppressor gene that inhibits 
\f0\b phosphorylation 
\f1\b0 activity in order to decrease rampant cell division. \cb1 \

\f3 \cf4 \cb3 \uc0\u9679  
\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 Retinoblastoma gene (RB) 
\f1\b0 is a tumor-suppressor gene that codes for a 
\f2\i retinoblastoma protein
\f1\i0 , which prevents excessive cell growth during 
\f0\b interphase
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \
\
