\f0\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Mendel\'92s Laws 
\f1\b0\fs36 \cf4 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 Gregor Mendel 
\f1\b0 studied genetics and proposed 
\f0\b three laws
\f1\b0 : \
\pard\tx560\pardeftab720\sl300\sa266\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 1.  \cf4 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Law of dominance 
\f1\b0 - 
\f0\b dominant 
\f1\b0 alleles mask the expression of 
\f0\b recessive 
\f1\b0 alleles. Mendel studied 
\f2\i plant height 
\f1\i0 to come to this conclusion. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 2.  \cf4 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Law of segregation 
\f1\b0 - homologous gene copies 
\f0\b separate 
\f1\b0 during meiosis (specifically 
\f2\i anaphase I
\f1\i0 ). Thus, Aa individuals will produce gametes with \'93A\'94 or \'93a\'94 alleles. \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 3. 
\f1\b0 \cf4 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 
\f0\b Law of independent assortment 
\f1\b0 - homologous chromosomes line up 
\f0\b independently 
\f1\b0 during 
\f2\i metaphase I 
\f1\i0 of meiosis so that alleles separate 
\f0\b randomly 
\f1\b0 (increases 
\f2\i genetic variability
\f1\i0 ). Metaphase II is different, during which 
\f2\i sister chromatids 
\f1\i0 are pulled apart instead. The law of independent assortment can produce 
\f0\b 2\cf4 \cb3 \up10 23 
\f1\b0 \cf4 \cb3 \up0 options (23 homologous chromosome pairs split). \
