\f0\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Crosses 
\f1\b0\fs36 \cf4 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 A 
\f0\b cross 
\f1\b0 refers to when two organisms are mated to produce offspring. \cb1 \
\cb3 A 
\f0\b test-cross 
\f1\b0 pairs an individual of 
\f2\i unknown 
\f1\i0 genotype with one that is 
\f2\i homozygous recessive
\f1\i0 . By looking at the 
\f0\b offspring 
\f1\b0 from a test-cross, we can determine the unknown genotype. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 True-breeding 
\f1\b0 organisms are 
\f2\i homozygous 
\f1\i0 for all the traits of interest. \cb1 \
\cb3 The 
\f0\b F1 generation 
\f1\b0 (aka 
\f0\b filial 1 hybrid
\f1\b0 ) is the 
\f2\i first 
\f1\i0 generation cross between true-breeding parents with different alleles. The offspring are all 
\f2\i heterozygous
\f1\i0 . \cb1 \
\cb3 The 
\f0\b F2 generation 
\f1\b0 (aka 
\f0\b filial 2 hybrid
\f1\b0 ) is the 
\f2\i second 
\f1\i0 generation cross between the heterozygous offspring from the F1 generation. This is where Mendel\'92s three laws can be studied. \cb1 \
\cb3 If these two generations are studied under 
\f0\b monohybrid crosses
\f1\b0 , then only a 
\f2\i single gene 
\f1\i0 is examined. In the F2 generation, the 
\f2\i genotype ratio 
\f0\i0\b (AA:Aa:aa) 
\f1\b0 should be 
\f0\b (1:2:1) 
\f1\b0 and the 
\f2\i phenotype ratio 
\f0\i0\b (dominant:recessive) 
\f1\b0 should be 
\f0\b (3:1)
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \
\cb3 On the other hand, a 
\f0\b dihybrid cross 
\f1\b0 examines the inheritance of 
\f2\i two genes 
\f1\i0 on 
\f0\b separate 
\f1\b0 chromosomes. Although the 
\f2\i genotype ratio 
\f1\i0 is complex in the F2 generation, just remember that the 
\f2\i phenotype ratio 
\f0\i0\b (both dominant:one dominant one recessive:one dominant one recessive:both recessive) 
\f1\b0 should be 
\f0\b (9:3:3:1)
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \

