\f0\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Gene linkage 
\f1\b0\fs36 \cf4 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 Linked genes 
\f1\b0 are found 
\f2\i close together 
\f1\i0 on the 
\f2\i same 
\f1\i0 chromosome. By looking at 
\f0\b recombination frequencies
\f1\b0 , we can deduce the relative distance between these genes. \cb1 \
\cb3 One 
\f0\b map unit 
\f1\b0 is defined as the chromosomal distance that would allow 
\f0\b 0.01 
\f1\b0 crossover events per generation. 
\f2\i 20 map units 
\f1\i0 would mean 0.2 crossover events occur between the two genes per generation, or 
\f2\i 20% chance of recombination
\f1\i0 . \cb1 \
\cb3 Recombination frequencies of 
\f0\b less than 50% 
\f1\b0 mean that the two genes are 
\f0\b linked
\f1\b0 . A random assortment of 
\f0\b unlinked 
\f1\b0 genes have 
\f0\b 50% recombinant progeny
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Linkage maps 
\f1\b0 can be drawn out using 
\f2\i map units 
\f1\i0 to 
\f0\b infer 
\f1\b0 the distance between genes on a chromosome. \cb1 \
\cb3 A 
\f0\b haplotype 
\f1\b0 is a group of genes that are usually inherited together because they are located in close proximity to each other. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sex-linked traits 
\f1\b0 come from genes located on the 
\f2\i sex chromosomes
\f1\i0 . Most sex-linked disorders have 
\f0\b X-chromosome linkage
\f1\b0 . Below are 
\f0\b three types 
\f1\b0 of sex-linked traits: \cb1 \
\pard\tx560\pardeftab720\sl300\sa266\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 1. X-linked dominant 
\f1\b0 - dominant inheritance on the X chromosome. 
\f0\b Any 
\f1\b0 offspring (male or female) that receive the affected allele 
\f2\i will end up with the disorder
\f1\i0 . \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 2. X-linked recessive 
\f1\b0 - recessive inheritance on the X chromosome. For males, only 
\f2\i one 
\f1\i0 affected allele is needed to cause the disorder. For females, 
\f2\i two 
\f1\i0 affected alleles are needed to cause the disorder because females have two X chromosomes. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 3. Y-linked 
\f1\b0 - inheritance on the Y chromosome. Can only be passed from 
\f0\b father to son
\f1\b0 . Will 
\f2\i always 
\f1\i0 be expressed whether it is dominant or recessive because males only have one Y chromosome. \cb1 \uc0\u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 Genomic imprinting 
\f1\b0 refers to genes that are expressed depending on 
\f2\i parental origin 
\f1\i0 and are influenced by 
\f0\b epigenetic factors
\f1\b0 . These genes are different from sex-linked traits because they can come from 
\f2\i autosomal chromosomes 
\f1\i0 (non-sex chromosomes) as well. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 X-inactivation 
\f1\b0 is the process by which one of a female\'92s X chromosomes is 
\f2\i inactivated
\f1\i0 , forming a 
\f0\b Barr body 
\f1\b0 and preventing 
\f2\i excess 
\f1\i0 transcription. However, a female carrier may become an 
\f0\b affected 
\f1\b0 individual for a disease if her unaffected X chromosome with a 
\f2\i normal wild-type allele 
\f1\i0 is inactivated, leaving behind a 
\f2\i recessive allele 
\f1\i0 that is not covered up. \cb1 \
\
